# StatusBadge

> Lightweight badges for system status and signals.  
> **Status**: Beta


## Demo

### Status Signals

Success, warning, error, info.

::TuffDemoWrapper{demo="StatusBadgeSignalsDemo" code-lang="vue"}
---
code: |
  <template>
    <TxStatusBadge text="Success" status="success" />
    <TxStatusBadge text="Warning" status="warning" />
    <TxStatusBadge text="Error" status="danger" />
    <TxStatusBadge text="Info" status="info" />
  </template>
---
::

### Dashboard Operations Status

In dashboard headers, `TxStatusBadge` usually works with `TxStatCard`, `TxProgressBar`, and `TuffSwitch` to summarize release, build, and sync health.

::TuffDemoWrapper{demo="ComponentsOperationsStatusDemo" code-lang="vue" title="Operations status panel" description="A dashboard status composition verified on the local Nexus page."}
---
code: |
  <template>
    <section class="grid gap-3">
      <TxStatusBadge text="Review done" status="success" size="sm" />
      <TxStatusBadge text="Build stable" status="success" os="linux" size="sm" />
      <TxStatusBadge text="Sync healthy" status-key="granted" size="sm" />
      <TxProgressBar :percentage="86" status="success" show-text />
    </section>
  </template>
---
::

## API (Lite)
::TuffPropsTable
---
rows:
  - name: text
    type: 'string'
    default: '-'
    description: 'Label text'
  - name: status
    type: "'success' | 'warning' | 'danger' | 'info' | 'muted'"
    default: 'info'
    description: 'Status type'
  - name: statusKey
    type: "'granted' | 'denied' | 'notDetermined' | 'unsupported' | string"
    default: "''"
    description: 'Permission/status key mapped to a tone'
  - name: icon
    type: 'string'
    default: "''"
    description: 'Custom icon class'
  - name: size
    type: "'sm' | 'md'"
    default: 'md'
    description: 'Size'
  - name: os
    type: "'macos' | 'windows' | 'linux'"
    default: '-'
    description: 'Optional platform icon'
  - name: osOnly
    type: 'boolean'
    default: 'false'
    description: 'Render only the platform icon'
---
::

## Contract

Explicit `status` takes precedence over `statusKey`. `statusKey` maps `granted/denied/notDetermined/unsupported` to success/danger/warning/muted, and unknown keys fall back to info. Platform icons render before the tone icon; `osOnly` hides the tone icon. The badge emits `click` when clicked.

## Review Notes

- Source: `packages/tuffex/packages/components/src/status-badge/src/TxStatusBadge.vue`
- Recommendation: prefer `statusKey` for backend status enums; use explicit `status` for page-local decisions.
- Accessibility: the component uses `role="status"`; badge text must express the state without relying on color alone.

